title: For Sale:  1798 Contract Musket
postcontent: Offered here is a rarely encountered 1798 Contract musket. This musket is one of approximately 14,000 muskets delivered between 1798 and 1801 from 26 different contractors. These muskets are rarely encountered today due to the poor overall quality of them when new. By the time of the War of 1812, most of these muskets had been condemned and sold as surplus from US stores. The musket offered here is nearly devois of markings, save for a US stamp at the rear of the lock. This is not dissimilar to marks found on Revolutionary War arms inventoried in the late 1780s. The only other markings are a single eagle head over raised P proof on the barrel, which according to George Moller's "American Military Shoulder Arms, Volume 2" is an indicator of Pennsylvania or Maryland production. There is also a small roman numeral XII on the left side of the upper barrel band, which may be an original assembly mark, or perhaps a reassembly mark following this musket's percussion alteration. Other parts do not bare this mark. It features a correct 44 and 1/16 inch barrel, and maintains the remnants of the detachable faceted iron pan typical of American muskets based on the French M1763/66 designs. This example managed to avoid being sent overseas to Africa or South America like so many, but was subsequently percussion altered. The percussion alteration is of the "Belgian" or "drum" style typically found on civilian alterations. However, the hammer is very well made, and is almost certainly of a military application. It is not too dissimilar from percussion alterations done by the firm of J.P. Murray during the Civil War. I feel that it is likely a Confederate alteration, but the exact arsenal or contractor is unknown at this time.The stock has been cleaned, lightly sanded, and reoiled at some time. Metal parts were apparently cleaned at the same time, but have taken an attractive gun metal patina. Although cleaned, the gun displays very well. The main issues worth noting are that the ramrod is about 3/4 of an inch short, and lacks threads, and that the percussion cone is mashed. The lock functions, albiet stiffly, and may have had the mainspring replaced at some point.Overall this is a nice example of a very scarce American military longarm that will make a nice addition to your collection.Please feel free to contact me with questions.

title: For Sale:  Confederate Altered M1816 Musket
postcontent: For sale is a Confederate percussion altered Model 1816 Musket. This example was altered to percussion by the Union Manufacturing Company of Richmond, Virginia. The Union Manufacturing Company performed aproximately 10,000 percussion alterations for the State of Virginia in 1861 and 1862. These arms are identified in by their unique "U" shaped bolster. This example was one of 160 Model 1816 muskets from Marine T. Wickham's contract owned by Virginia in 1860. This musket has been cleaned, both metal and stock, but still displays well. The stock has been sanded and refinished, but a partial cartouche remains. The metal is developing a pewter patina and is free from all active rust. The percussion nipple is missing, and the bolster displays worn threads, but a replacement cone could probably be fitted with minimal issues. The ramrod is full length and retains the original threaded end for the attachment of cleaning implements. I am confident that the hammer is a replacement, and is probably from a Henry Leman alteration. It is of similar proportion to the original percussion hammer and displays well enough. With some searching a replacement hammer could probably be had.For the money this is a very nice musket that fills an important part of any Confederate collection, or collection of percussion altered arms.Shipping can be arranged. Please contact me with any questions.

title: For Sale:  Springfield Armory TRP "Chris Kyle" #326 of 1000
postcontent: This .45 ACP pistol was inspired by this quote from Kyle’s autobiography American Sniper: “In 2004, I brought over a Springfield TRP Operator, which used a .45 caliber round. It had a 1911 body style, with custom grips and a rail system that let me add a light and laser combo. Black, it had a bull barrel and was an excellent gun – until it took a frag for me in Fallujah. I was actually able to get it repaired – those Springfields are tough.” In a wide partnership that includes the Chris Kyle Frog Foundation — with Kyle’s wife Taya at the helm — Springfield Armory, the retailer Gun Broker, and the upcoming National Rifle Association convention, the number one pistol in the series is currently up for auction on gunbroker.com. The pistol’s in-person transfer from original owner Taya Kyle to the buyer will be made at the Springfield Armory booth at , located the NRA show in Louisville. Bidding has already begun online, but a dramatic, live-bidding finale is planned. Taya Kyle was presented with the pistol by Springfield Armory at the 2016 SHOT Show. Her immediate response included plans for a benefit auction. Springfield’s president and chief executive officer, Dennis Reese, will also be on hand for the announcement of the winning bid, and will present a check to Kyle, representing the Chris Kyle Frog Foundation, in the amount of the final bid. “We felt it appropriate to make this special edition pistol to honor [Chris Kyle’s] memory and support the ongoing work of the foundation,” Reese said. “Very much like American hero Chris Kyle, this pistol is truly one of a kind.” Springfield will produce one thousand TRP Legend Series pistols, each with a unique serial number ranging from CK0001 through CK1000. The first gun in the series was presented to Taya Kyle, who donated it to benefit the foundation named for her husband. In addition to the donation of proceeds from the first in the series, Springfield has volunteered to donate a portion of the profit from the sales of the other firearms in the limited edition to the Chris Kyle Frog Foundation, which offers support to military and first-responders. As part of the Springfield Legend pistol series, the TRP Chris Kyle series feature a five-inch stainless steel match grade barrel, low-profile three-dot tritium combat sights, and black and gray G10 grips with American flag engraving. The slides are forged carbon steel with black Nitride treatment. A full-length guide rod by National Match completes the 8.6-inch long, government model 1911. Each pistol ships with two seven-round stainless steel magazines with slam pads. Pistols in the series will be packaged in a serialized mahogany presentation case. A memorial copy of the best-selling book, American Sniper, signed by Taya Kyle, will be included, as will a .999 pure silver Chris Kyle limited edition challenge coin, and a Springfield certificate of authenticity.
